    <title>Combined summary - Segmented Block Relaying BIP draft.</title>
    <updated>2023-06-06T07:14:44.818402+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2012-September/001814.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>In 2012, the Bitcoin community engaged in discussions that covered various aspects of Bitcoin, Open Transactions, and Ripple. One of the topics discussed was the use of Merkle trees in Bitcoin, which is considered an efficient way of verifying the integrity of large sets of data with minimal computational resources. The email thread also discusses ways to parallelize block downloads while preventing re-download of already known transactions.Matthew Mitchell proposed a draft proposal for improving block relaying and validation in Bitcoin by enabling parallel processing and eliminating redundancy in the process. Mitchell explains that this becomes more beneficial as blocks sizes increase. However, there is a question raised regarding the need to send the hash tree. On September 11, 2012, Gregory Maxwell questioned the value of a proposal to reduce the size of Bitcoin transactions, arguing that the scarcity of block space is what makes Bitcoin attractive and economically sane. The scarcity of block space in the Bitcoin network makes it economically sustainable and attractive. Instead of changing the protocol, off-chain transactions denominated in bitcoin could be used through distributed cryptographic banks that maintain trust through Open Transaction contracts containing proof of agreement. However, this proposal has been criticized as it may make bitcoin useless.In addition, Matt Corallo discussed the idea of segmenting blocks, stating that it would add little to nothing with any sane block size. He argued that removing the current 1MB cap on block size would compromise the core economic promises of the system as well as the long-term security of the network. The issue of block size was also discussed in an email exchange from 2012, where it was questioned what would happen if Bitcoin demand started pushing the block sizes into megabytes. The limit of ~0.95MB needed to be changed eventually for Bitcoin to grow that far, but the finite size creates non-trivial fees, which are necessary for honest economic motivation to mine.Furthermore, the email thread includes a discussion on the use of six new messages in the Bitcoin protocol that enable nodes to relay segments of blocks before receiving the entire block. Mike Hearn expresses disagreement with Gregory on various points related to Bitcoin and believes that Bloom filtering is much more important. He argues that incentivizing miners and maintaining stronger security should be enough motivation to prevent people from setting the difficulty to zero.The writer suggests analyzing how beneficial their proposal for a simpler protocol for Bitcoin transactions would be and measuring peer behavior, as well as discussing these issues well in advance to avoid any last-minute problems. Finally, the conversation also covers various aspects of Bitcoin, Open Transactions, and Ripple, pointing out their strengths and limitations.</summary>
